Mr Kitavi said that as soon as the remand prisoners collapsed, the local multi-sectoral Covid-19 committee met to discuss the matter.
However, a post-mortem report revealed that the suspects could have died of injuries inflicted at the police station or lack of sufficient oxygen due to congestion.
The revelation now puts the police in a spot.
Internal injuries 
Government Chief Pathologist Dr Johansen Oduor disapproved the police theory that Covid-19 claimed the lives of the pair.
According to Dr Oduor, who performed the autopsy at the Kerugoya Referral Hospital mortuary, both victims had internal head and stomach injuries and lacked enough oxygen.
"The victims could have succumbed to injuries they suffered at the police station or insufficient oxygen occasioned by congestion in the cells," he told reporters.
Dr Oduor said investigations have started to establish who fatally attacked the victims while in police custody.
Following the post-mortem, families of the two villagers are now crying out for justice.
Mr Musyoka’s first widow, Jeniffer Njeri, said she was shocked to learn that her husband did not lose his life to Covid-19 as had been alleged by the police.
"It has now been established beyond any reasonable doubt that my husband died after being attacked at the police station. He had injuries on the legs, hands and head. Those responsible for the death of my husband should be arrested and prosecuted," she said.



