Ms Njeri said it would be very difficult for her and her co-wife to provide for their nine children.
"Mr Musyoka, who was a mechanic, was the sole breadwinner for our family and we shall surely suffer following his demise," she added.
And Ms Loise Nyawira said Mr Njeru, her son, worked as a boda-boda rider in Thiba Village. He is survived by a wife and one child.
"Sadly, officers who are entrusted to protect our children are the ones who are turning against them," said Ms Nyawira.
She said officers implicated in the death of her son should not go unpunished.
The families said the two victims were in the local market at night when they were seized by the officers for allegedly flouting curfew rules and booked at the station.
"At first, we were told they suffered from Covid-19 which later killed them. We doubted the police information because their bodies had serious injuries," said Ms Nyawira.
The families said they had obtained results of Covid-19 tests on their relatives, which indicated that they were free from the disease.
"We have the results which show that our relatives were not sick," Ms Nyawira said. Ezekiel Oduor Okiru, 20, was allegedly shot by police on patrol on Friday night for not wearing a mask. Suspects were released on cash bail and are expected to appear in courts today. Residents of Mombasa have been eagerly waiting the commissioning of the bridge. Ms Nthenya was freed without any charges being preferred against her. Just last week, Justice James Rika recused himself from the case after tempers flared in court.